  "doc_id": "39255",
  "text": "It is possible that 5-HT2C receptor-mediated inhibition of mesolimbic DA function may contribute to the effects of 5-HT on novelty-related behavior. Accordingly, firing rates of VTA DA neurons are suppressed by administration of 5-HT2C receptor agonists; conversely, firing rates are enhanced by 5-HT2C receptor antagonist treatment [CITATION_1] . Previous anatomical and electrophysiological studies indicated that these effects may result from the activation of inhibitory GABAergic interneurons expressing 5-HT2C receptors [CITATION_2] Gobert et al., 2000; [CITATION_3] . The observed absence of phenotypic differences in baseline NAcc dialysate DA levels using standard in vivo microdialysis methods does not preclude potential alterations in dopaminergic neurotransmission, because spillover of neurotransmitters into the extracellular space may not parallel synaptic release [CITATION_4] . Additional studies using the no net flux quantitative microdialysis method will provide a more sensitive indication of basal mesolimbic DA neurotransmission.",
